  "prompt_text": "Explain the concept of Big-O notation. Rank the following: O(n!), O(2^n), O(n^2), O(n log n), O(n), O(log n), O(1).",
  "response_text": "Big-O notation is a mathematical notation that describes the upper bound of the complexity of an algorithm. It characterizes the worst-case scenario for how long an algorithm takes to run as the size of its input grows. Essentially, it tells us how the runtime or space usage scales with the input size \\(n\\).\n\nHere's the ranking from most complex to least complex:\n\n1. **O(n!)** - This represents algorithms where the number of operations grows factorially with the input size \\(n\\). An example is the traveling salesman problem when solved using brute force.\n2. **O(2^n)** - This represents algorithms with exponential growth. A classic example is the recursive solution to the Tower of Hanoi problem.\n3. **O(n^2)** - Quadratic time complexity is common in nested loops, such as bubble sort.\n4. **O(n \\log n)** - This includes efficient sorting algorithms like merge sort and quicksort.\n5. **O(n)** - Linear time complexity is achieved when the processing time increases linearly with the input size, such as in simple for-loops that iterate over the input once.\n6. **O(\\log n)** - Logarithmic time complexity is seen in algorithms that divide the problem into smaller parts, like binary search.\n7. **O(1)** - Constant time complexity means the execution time does not depend on the input size, such as accessing an element in an array by index.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 9\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
